args: The Milon Plains are New Alberian territory,\nlocated directly on the border between the\nfledgling kingdom and the Dyrenell Empire.
Several days ago, the imperial army invaded the\nplains in an attempt to gain a foothold in the area.
The company dispatched to quell this threat\nis one whose deeds of valor are known across\nthe continent: the White Sparrow Knights.
Now, Vice Captain Patia leads a detachment\ndown the area's main highway, hoping to catch\nthe imperial force in a pincer attack.
Our main force should have taken up\npositions on the Milon Plains by now.\nWhat of the civilian militia in the rear?
No new information to report, ma'am.\nThey appear to be making their way\nalong the highway without issue.
Understood. We'd best not slow our\npace if we want to be the first ones\nto the enemy!
The main force sends word of an ambush\nin the woods just ahead of our position!
An ambush, eh? The imperials must have\nrealized we'd be sending a detachment.
It seems so, ma'am. They were probably\nplaced to guard against attacks from\nthe highway.
I suppose it was too much to hope we\nwould be able to march right up to the\nenemy's front door without resistance.
If we fall back now, we can pass over the\nnorthern highway. It would take more time,\nbut we can avoid a fight.
Stay in formation until I give the signal!\nWatch each other's backs!
Their defensive posture is meaningless\nagainst our far superior numbers.\nSurround and crush them, men!
Make light of us, will you?! Haaah!
I have a clear path to the commander...\nStrike true, my blade! Haaaah!
Well, heck. Looks like the White Sparrow\nCorps are takin' the fight to the imperials.
Uh, are we sure we wanna be here?\nI mean, we're just some ragtag militia,\nbut them folks are professional soldiers.
Y-yeah, I know... But we didn't come all\nthis way just to sit out the fight!
You're right... Hey, listen up, everybody!\nWe're gonna fight!
We're going to be wiped out here...\nRetreat! Retreeeeat!
Ha! Look at them imperials run!

Forgive me, Vice Captain, but should
we not chase down those fleeing men?
If they bring word back to the stronghold,
the imperials will know that we're here.
The imperials predicted our presence when\nthey set their ambush. Confirmation will\nmake little difference at this point.
Now then! To the people's militia, I say:\nYour performance in battle was splendid!
Thank you, ma'am. Reckon I'm just glad\nwe worked up the courage to fight.
Then remember it well, for courage is the\ngreatest weapon on a battlefield, and the\nshield by which you protect your fellows.
From this point forward, we serve as one.\nAll together, men! Forwaaaaard, march!

Sir, I bring word! Patia's forces stayed
the course and broke through the enemy
ambush. She then joined with the local
militia and continued her advance.
A short time ago, her force launched an\nattack on the enemy's main camp.\nThe imperials are in complete disarray!
Forgive me, sir, but was it not somewhat\nreckless for her to march directly into an\nambush after being warned about it?
Oh, it was completely reckless.\nHowever, it also makes a good\namount of sense.

There are multiple reasons, but first,
she presumably valued the time lost
to taking a detour over the danger
of fighting the ambush.

A detachment pulling off an assault before
the main battle begins throws the enemy
forces off guard and reduces the losses
our main force will suffer.
In addition to that, her attack served as\nvaluable combat experience for the militia.
So having the militia join the attack\nwas just some manner of...drill?
In a sense, yes. History gives us many\nexamples of civilian militias losing heart\nas they face down the abyss of true battle.
What do you think would happen if they\nwere to lose their nerve? If their will to\nfight took flight in the midst of combat?
If that happened, sir, there would likely\nbe great losses for both the militia and\nthe professional soldiers alike.

Precisely. Which is why I suspect the Vice
Captain wanted to let the militia share in
the experience of a victory before such a
thing could come to pass.
On the battlefield, belief in oneself\nbecomes courage—and courage is\nthe greatest of all weapons.
So while I agree that the Vice Captain may\nhave been reckless, I also know she has a\ndeep understanding of the nature of war.
You've only just enlisted, yes?\nLet me give you some advice:
If you're surprised by every little thing the\nVice Captain does, you'd best grow a\nsecond heart to absorb all the shocks.
Heh. Now then, we'd best be on our way.\nBring word to the troops that we are to\nmove out at once!
